Animam relinquam. Comp. Heaut. iii. 1. 70. —54. Is, quod mihi, &a Madame Dacier rejects this line, because it is also to be found in the Phormio. But it is no uncommon thing with our author to use the same expression or verse in different places, especially on familiar occasions. There is no impropriety in it here, and the soregoing hemistich is rather lame without it. The propriety of consulting Micio, or·Demea's present ill-humour with him, are of no consequence.
